The job-to-be-done (in one sentence)

Make sure every order has a clean, current, mutually agreed state—and that the next action is always owned, messaged, and time-boxed.

⸻

Key capabilities

1) Order “Digital Thread” (single source of truth)

For every order, maintain an event timeline:
	•	PO received → validated → confirmed (ATP/CTP) → allocated → pick/pack → shipped → delivered → invoiced → claims/returns
	•	Attachments: PO PDFs, COAs, packing lists, proof of delivery, photos, temperature logs, etc.
	•	Links: ERP order ID, WMS shipment ID, carrier tracking, EDI doc IDs

2) Multi-party messaging that’s structured (not just chat)

Every message has:
	•	Intent: confirm / request info / propose change / alert / escalate
	•	Fields: PO#, SKU, qty, ship-to, requested ship date, promised date, incoterms, carrier, lot, temperature range, etc.
	•	Required response: “Approve / Reject / Provide missing field / Choose option A/B”

So the AI can parse replies reliably and close loops.

3) Exception detection + resolution playbooks

Examples:
	•	Inventory short / backorder risk
	•	Carrier delay / missed pickup
	•	Address validation failure
	•	Credit hold / compliance doc missing
	•	Substitution request (SKU swap)
	•	Partial shipment decision needed
	•	Temperature excursion / damage claim

Each exception maps to a playbook:
	•	Who to notify
	•	What to ask for
	•	What options to offer
	•	What SLA clock starts
	•	When to escalate

4) “Options engine” (propose, don’t impose)

When something breaks, the AI proposes resolution paths:
	•	Split shipment vs hold for full
	•	Expedite carrier vs push promise date
	•	Alternate DC or distributor
	•	Substitute SKU / lot
	•	Reroute shipment
…and presents tradeoffs (cost, lead time, fill rate, penalty risk).

5) Approval + governance (critical)

No silent autonomous changes.
	•	AI can draft messages and propose changes
	•	Writes to ERP/WMS/TMS require explicit approval (human or rule-based delegation)
	•	Full audit log: who approved what, when, and why

⸻

System architecture (practical)

A) Integrations layer

Connectors:
	•	ERP (SAP/Oracle/NetSuite/Dynamics)
	•	WMS (Manhattan/Körber)
	•	TMS / carrier APIs (project44/FourKites, FedEx/UPS)
	•	EDI (850/855/856/810) via translator
	•	Email + Slack/Teams + customer portals

B) Canonical data model

Normalize everything into:
	•	Parties, locations, SKUs, orders, shipments, invoices
	•	Status codes (standardized)
	•	“Commitments” (promised ship date, delivery date, qty confirmed)

C) Event bus + state machine
	•	Every change becomes an event
	•	Order state is derived from events
	•	Exceptions are triggered by rules + ML anomaly signals

D) LLM + rules engine (hybrid)
	•	Rules engine for deterministic stuff (SLA, status transitions, thresholds)
	•	LLM for:
	•	Parsing unstructured messages / attachments
	•	Drafting responses
	•	Summarizing threads
	•	Turning “human talk” into structured fields

E) Case management UI

A cockpit for ops:
	•	Queue of open exceptions
	•	Each case shows: status, parties, deadlines, message history, recommended actions
	•	One-click: send drafted message, request approval, escalate

